    <title>Combined summary - Extension for BIP-0070 to support recurring payments</title>
    <updated>2023-06-08T02:03:15.398260+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2014-January/004232.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Bitcoin core developer Jeff Garzik has proposed a new BIP to enable recurring payments and subscriptions in the Bitcoin network. Stephane Brossier has suggested an extension to the Payment Protocol (BIP-0070) to address this need. The proposal aims to allow customers to pay for subscription-based services using Bitcoin, with advantages such as giving users control over their subscriptions and opening the door to subscription management tools in wallets. The process involves initial registration, ongoing payments, subscription change (optional), and cancellation of the subscription. The wallet would be responsible for polling the merchant for any due payments associated with the subscription to ensure that payments match the contract without explicit approval from the customer. There are concerns about implementing the protocol, such as triggering it off the existing payment protocol, defining the payment schedule data structures, and allowing pre-submission of time-locked transactions.Two developers have committed a prototype implementation of the protocol using bitcoinj. The PaymentFrequencyType enum in the Bitcoin protocol only allows for weekly, monthly, quarterly, and annual payments, so the proposal suggests making the protocol more flexible by dropping quarterly payments and allowing for daily payments and specifying recurring cycles as every n*period. Additionally, merchants may request subscriptions with the option to pause or cancel them, and textual reminders to send money may be preferred over actual recurring payment automation. The team completed the second iteration of their prototype, having added cancellation and upgrade/downgrade options. They have checked in both the bitcoinj and php server to test it and are waiting for feedback. Another developer proposed an extension to the Payment Protocol (bip-0070) for recurring payments using Kill Bill as a merchant server. One solution for managing payments is to schedule recurring payments at regular intervals but with the ability to pause or cancel them at any time. Jeff Garzik outlined that recurring payments and subscriptions are frequently requested features in the Bitcoin network. However, implementing this feature would require careful planning and execution, as the situation is similar to HTML5 local storage, where the remote merchant wants to initiate persistent behavior. Centralized services like Coinbase or Blockchain.info would have an easier time implementing it, but decentralized wallet clients may face challenges. It is suggested that a textual reminder to send money may be preferred over actual recurring payment automation to insert additional human thought and review into the process.The proposal has advantages over traditional payment methods including user control over subscriptions and opens the door for subscription management tools in wallets. Feedback on the high-level proposal is welcome. Two developers have committed a prototype implementation of the protocol using bitcoinj. The email thread discusses a proposal for a protocol to enable recurring payments in Bitcoin, which is an extension of BIP-0070. The proposed protocol aims to allow customers to pay for subscription-based services using Bitcoin, with advantages such as giving users control over their subscriptions and opening the door to subscription management tools in wallets. The email provides a high-level description of the protocol, including the flow of operations, creation of the subscription, ongoing payments, subscription change (optional), and cancellation of the subscription. The email also addresses some concerns and issues with regards to implementing the proposed protocol. A team is proposing a protocol to enable recurring payments in Bitcoin as an extension of BIP-0070. The objective is for customers to subscribe to services and have wallets automatically make recurring payments without intervention, as long as payments match the subscription contract. The protocol introduces an efficient way of managing subscriptions using Bitcoin, and it will be useful for both merchants and customers.Overall, the proposal is to allow recurring payments in Bitcoin through a protocol that enables subscription-based services. The team has implemented a prototype and is seeking feedback to improve the protocol and integrate it with merchant servers. One suggestion for managing payments is to schedule recurring payments at regular intervals, but with the ability to pause or cancel them at any time.</summary>
